<div>
    <h1>Json:</h1>
    <h2>
        Working with JSON data
    </h2>
    <pre>
        Working with JSON data in JavaScript typically involves two main operations: parsing and stringifying. 
    </pre>
    <h2>
        Parsing and stringify
    </h2>
    <pre>
        // Sample JSON data (string)
        const jsonString = '{"name": "abid", "age": 25, "city": "Nagpur"}';

        // Parsing JSON string to JavaScript object
        const parsedData = JSON.parse(jsonString);

        // Accessing properties of the parsed object
        console.log('Name:', parsedData.name);
        console.log('Age:', parsedData.age);
        console.log('City:', parsedData.city);

        // Creating a JavaScript object
        const person = {
            name: 'Arif',
            age: 30,
            city: 'Mumbai'
        };

        // Stringifying JavaScript object to JSON string
        const jsonStringFromObject = JSON.stringify(person);

        // Displaying the JSON string
        console.log('JSON String from Object:', jsonStringFromObject);
    </pre>
    <pre>
        JSON.parse: This function is used to parse a JSON string and convert it into a JavaScript object. 
        The resulting object can be accessed like any other JavaScript object.

        JSON.stringify: This function is used to convert a JavaScript object into a JSON string. 
        The resulting string can be transmitted over the network, stored in a file, 
        or used wherever a string representation of the object is needed.
    </pre>
</div>
